<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;has been recently identified.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains information about the work you are citing, including the author&#8217;s name, the newspaper title, and publication date.
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
Footnotes are placed in numerical order at the bottom of the page. When references to the same work follow each other with no other references in&#45;between, use a shortened citation in the first instance (Example B). However, if you are instructed by your tutor or lecturer to provide a full reference in the footnote the first time a work is cited, see Example A. If the work is cited again, use the short form (Example B).
<br><br>
If other references to the same article follow directly after, replace the author&#8217;s name and title and publication details with <strong>ibid</strong> (Example C). Page numbers are not usually given.
<br><br>
<strong>Example A</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">1. David Orange, &#34;Something Went Wrong in Plane Crash, Experts Say,&#34; <em>Herald Tribune</em>, December 15, 2056.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example B</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">7. Orange, &#34;Something Went Wrong in Plane Crash.&#34;</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example C</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">8. Ibid.</span>
</blockquote>
